1) Effects of weather on bikeshare trips¶

Hypothesis : Days with better weather had longer and a greater number of rides vs the days with bad weather

In [8]:
# Clean the data
# fix null zip codes for trips
trip.zip_code = trip.zip_code.replace(np.nan, 0)

# convert dates to datetime objects
trip.start_date = pd.to_datetime(trip['start_date']).dt.date
trip.end_date = pd.to_datetime(trip['end_date']).dt.date
weather.date = pd.to_datetime(weather['date']).dt.date

# convert weather zipcodes to string
weather.zip_code = weather.zip_code.astype(str)

# convert precipitation to float and replace null values 
weather.precipitation_inches = weather.precipitation_inches.str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float).replace(np.nan, 0)
weather.mean_temperature_f = weather.mean_temperature_f.replace(np.nan, 0)
weather.mean_dew_point_f = weather.mean_dew_point_f.replace(np.nan, 0)
weather.mean_humidity = weather.mean_humidity.replace(np.nan, 0)
weather.mean_visibility_miles = weather.mean_visibility_miles.replace(np.nan, 0)
weather.mean_wind_speed_mph = weather.mean_wind_speed_mph.replace(np.nan, 0)
In [9]:
#filter the data to only consider zip codes for which the weather data is available
tripWeather = trip.loc[trip.zip_code.isin(weather.zip_code)]

# ensure trip dates for which weather data is available
tripWeather = tripWeather.loc[trip['start_date'] >= weather['date'].min()]
tripWeather = tripWeather.loc[trip['end_date'] <= weather['date'].max()]

tripWeather = tripWeather.rename(columns={'start_date': 'date'})

# Add a calculated column for total trips for a date
tripWeatherDur = tripWeather.groupby(['zip_code', 'date'])['duration'].sum().reset_index(name = 'duration')
tripWeather = tripWeather.groupby(['zip_code', 'date'])['id'].count().reset_index(name = 'total')


# # # Merge the trip and weather dataframes 
tripWeather = tripWeather.merge(weather, how='inner', on=['date', 'zip_code'])
tripWeatherDur = tripWeatherDur.merge(weather, how='inner', on=['date', 'zip_code'])

# find the mean values for all zip codes
tripWeatherMean = tripWeather.groupby('date').aggregate('mean').reset_index()
tripWeatherDurMean = tripWeatherDur.groupby('date').aggregate('mean').reset_index()

# Compute the regression between weather and number of trips and individual correlation between elements
X = tripWeatherMean.iloc[:, 3:]
temp = tripWeatherMean.mean_temperature_f
dew = tripWeatherMean.mean_dew_point_f
humidity = tripWeatherMean.mean_humidity
visibility = tripWeatherMean.mean_visibility_miles
wind = tripWeatherMean.mean_wind_speed_mph
prec = tripWeatherMean.precipitation_inches
y = tripWeatherMean.iloc[:, 2]
reg = LinearRegression().fit(X, y)
print('Reg = ', reg.score(X, y))
print('Temp = ', y.corr(temp))
print('Dew = ', y.corr(dew))
print('Humidity = ', y.corr(humidity))
print('Visibility = ', y.corr(visibility))
print('Wind = ', y.corr(wind))
print('Precipitation = ', y.corr(prec))

In [10]:
#Since we know how many trips are taken from each station we can create a data frame summarizing how many times a station
#is being used and add additional metrics to clearly see which stations are the most popular and if they are being properly
#utilized by adding the number of hours that bike station has been vacant.
most_trips = trips_start.groupby(trips_start.start_station_id).count().sort_values(ascending=False, 
                                                                                   by = 'duration')
longest_trips = trips_start.groupby(trips_start.start_station_id).mean().round(1).sort_values(ascending=False, 
                                                                                   by = 'duration')
trip = pd.DataFrame()
trip['Number of Services'] = most_trips['duration']
trip['Average Duration of Rides'] = longest_trips['duration']
trip['Hours without available bikes'] = time_empty['Hours without available bikes']

As we can see from this data there are a number of stations that are very popular but are heavily under utilized due to its bike availability. Stations such as 70 and 60 while being in top 5 of the most used stations have the most time spent without any available bikes which hurts the potential gains of the company. To further test this concept we are going to see what the most popular end stations are to better understand if there are just not enough units of bikes in circulation or if there should be more bike stations for customers to use.

Surprisingly the list of most used end stations is exactly the same as our list of start stations. This means that those bike stations are under heavy traffic daily and they are in fact lacking the number of available units rather than in need of additional bike stations being build. Based on this data its safe to assume that adding bikes in circulation would result in increased profits and better market coverage.

Out[7]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x2613c1911c0>

As we can see, certain zip codes have a disproportionately high number of bicycles for their populations, whereas most areas hover at less than 1 bike per 1000 people. Further datasets are required at this point to correlate bike and dock availability with economic status. However, based on the analysis above, this low availability of bikes could merely mean that the bikes are heavily utilized within the zip code, or as a means of transportation. However, if we compare this against the number of docks, we see that certain areas also have a disproportionately high number of docks, and these are surprisingly the same areas where the number of bikes available are disproportionately high. We can confirm this by looking at the sg1 dataframe above the plots.

4) Subscriber behavior¶

Mine bike share data to define and contrast the behaviour of subscribers and casual users. A through understanding of these two distinct user groups can inform decisions regarding infrastructure investment and pricing that will ultimately:

  • best serve the unique needs of frequent and casual users;
  • convert casual users to subscribers; and
  • expand the overall reach of the service.
